# Lab Name
DOM XSS in document.write sink using source location.search

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – DOM-Based XSS

## Objective
Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability and execute JavaScript in the browser.

## Entry Point
URL query string (location.search)

## Exploitation Type
DOM-Based XSS

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and inspect the search functionality

2. Observe that the application reads user input from:
   location.search

3. Notice that the value is written directly to the page using:
   document.write()

4. Since no sanitization or encoding is applied, user-controlled input can be injected into the DOM

5. Craft a payload that breaks out of the existing HTML context and injects JavaScript

6. Append the payload to the search parameter in the URL

7. Load the URL in the browser

8. Observe that the JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

"><script>alert(1)</script>

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript through a DOM-based XSS vulnerability.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Manipulation of page content
- Account compromise

## Mitigation
- Avoid using document.write() with untrusted data
- Sanitize and validate all user-controlled input
- Use safe DOM manipulation methods such as textContent
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Perform proper output encoding

## Learning
DOM-based XSS occurs entirely in the browser when client-side JavaScript processes untrusted data insecurely.
Functions such as document.write() should never be used with user-controlled input without proper sanitization.
